Content:
I‚Äôm actually not even in CS myself, I‚Äôm a computer engineer in the ECE department and it‚Äôs made absolutely no difference in my career as a software engineer. Most people don‚Äôt care about major nowadays. A lot of non cs friends are going to big companies in FAANG as well as companies like airbnb lyft etc. There‚Äôs also a lot of opportunities in research as well. A lot of the best labs on campus are not in the CSE department but in the Cognitive Science Department (Design Lab) and other engineering departments.

That being said, I‚Äôm not saying you shouldn‚Äôt aim to switch over to CSE if that‚Äôs what you‚Äôre passionate about and if you think you‚Äôd have a better time in the major. For example, I know I would be having a more fun time taking more CSE classes than ECE classes. But you shouldn‚Äôt stress yourself out too much over it, especially since it is a lottery system (I failed the lottery twice). Make sure that class is really about gaining the skills necessary to grow and do what you‚Äôre interested in, and not just so you can change the major and gpa listed on your transcripts

Author: for loop#9853
Content: Im not sure about primes but i would approach this problem by solving by proving the contra positive. The contrapositive of (: n^2 even ‚Äî> n even)  would be  (n odd ‚Äî> n^2 odd) since an odd number is 2k + 1 (for any integer k) n^2 odd would be (2k+1)^2 = 4k^2 +2k + 1 = 2(2k^2  + k) + 1 = 0. If you let Q = (2k^2 + k) you see that 2(Q) + 1 = 0 which means that n^2 is also odd. Now since you proved the contrapositive you have also proved the original.

Author: shbiswas#1576
Content: Question: would it be better to take cse 20 at ucsd or cc, or does it really just not matter

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
@shbiswas, it doesn't really matter.

Basically, you need to complete both of these lower div series before you take CSE 100, which blocks you from taking most upper divs

CSE 11 -> CSE 12 ./ 15L -> CSE 30
CSE 20 -> CSE 21

Because of this, taking CSE 20 doesn't really get you ahead timewise, just because you end up still having to complete CSE 11 / 12 / 30 before you can take 100. That being said, taking it at CC does give you the advantage of being able to take an additional GE in lieu of CSE 20, but if taking it in cc costs you extra money, i would just take it at ucsd

Author: Edward#3697
Content:
What: CSE 125 game demos
Day: Friday, June 5
Time: 4-5:30pm
Where: Online (link will be on the following page)
Info: https://cse125.ucsd.edu/2020/groups.html

The groups in the Spring 2020 CSE 125 class will be presenting and demoing their projects on Friday, June 5, from 4-5:30pm...streaming live online!  We would like to invite everyone to join us to watch the live demos.The following page will have the streaming link when it's
created next week:

  https://cse125.ucsd.edu/2020/groups.html

The goal of CSE 125 is for the students to experience the design and implementation of a large, complex, distributed software system with real-time constraints, and do it in large groups. For motivation, the project assignment was to build a distributed, real-time, 3D, multiplayer game...in 10 weeks...and this quarter, remotely (!).

This course is also an opportunity for the students to take everything that they have learned in their classes over the years and apply it to one project in one quarter.  As you'll see, they have learned a tremendous amount: the projects are amazing. For a preview, see the group web pages:

  https://cse125.ucsd.edu/2020/groups.html

Each group web page has a project design, project specification, weekly status reports, screenshots, etc. -- together, these documents chart the progress of the groups and the evolution of their projects throughout the quarter.

At the demos we will start with a brief introduction to the course, and then each of the groups will present and demo their project.

We hope you can join us!

Geoff Voelker, Edward Chen, and the Students of CSE 125
